have spread to [[England]] with two cases among Chinese nationals staying in a hotel in [[York]] on 31 January 2020.\n\n== Timeline ==\n=== January 2020 ===\n{{seealso|2020 coronavirus pandemic in London}}\nOn 31 January, two members of a family of Chinese nationals staying in a hotel in [[York]], one of whom studied at the [[University of York]], became the first confirmed cases of COVID-19 in the UK. Upon confirmation, they were transferred from [[Hull University Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust|Hull University Teaching Hospital]] to a specialist isolation facility, a designated High Consequence Infectious Diseases Unit in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]]'s [[Royal Victoria Infirmary]].<ref name=Ball31Jan2020>{{Cite news|last=Ball|first=Tom|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/hunt-for-contacts-of-coronavirus-stricken-pair-in-york-dh363qf8k|title=Hunt for contacts of coronavirus-stricken pair in York|date=31 January 2020|work=[[The Times]]|access-date=6 March 2020|url-status=live|last2=Wace|first2=Charlotte |issn=0140-0460|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204105559/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/hunt-for-contacts-of-coronavirus-stricken-pair-in-york-dh363qf8k|archive-date=4 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=Lancet14March2020>{{Cite journal|last=Moss|first=Peter|last2=Barlow|first2=Gavin|last3=Easom|first3=Nicholas|last4=Lillie|first4=Patrick|last5=Samson|first5=Anda|date=14 March 2020|title=Lessons for managing high-consequence infections from first COVID-19 cases in the UK|url=https://www.thelancet.com/action/showPdf?pii=S0140-6736%2820%2930463-3|journal=The Lancet |volume=395|issue=10227|pages=e46|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30463-3|issn=0140-6736|pmid=32113507}}</ref>\n\nOn the same day, an [[evacuations related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|evacuation flight]] from Wuhan landed at [[RAF Brize Norton]] and the passengers, none of whom were showing symptoms, were taken to quarantine, in a staff residential block at [[Arrowe Park Hospital]] on the [[Wirral Peninsula|Wirral]].<ref name=\"BBC-51318691\">{{cite web |title=Britons in Wuhan to return home on Friday |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51318691 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=31 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131024212/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51318691 |archive-date=31 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> There had previously been contention over whether the government should assist the repatriation of UK passport holders from the most affected areas in China, or restrict travel from affected regions altogether.<ref name=\"Standard27Jan2020\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/coronavirus-evacuate-britons-china-virus-hubei-warning-boris-johnson-a4345571.html|title=Ministers came under growing pressure today to evacuate Britons from the Chinese region shut down by the killer coronavirus.|date=27 January 2020|work=London Evening Standard|access-date=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222145256/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/coronavirus-evacuate-britons-china-virus-hubei-warning-boris-johnson-a4345571.html|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"McHutchon25Jan2020\">{{Cite news|last=McHutchon|first=David|url=https://www.technicalpolitics.com/articles/too-weak-too-slow-the-uk-governments-dithering-response-to-the-wuhan-coronavirus-increases-the-risk-of-major-loss-of-life/|title=Too Weak, Too Slow: The UK Government's Dithering Response to the Wuhan Coronavirus Increases the Risk of Major Loss of Life|date=25 January 2020|work=|access-date=26 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222131735/https://www.technicalpolitics.com/articles/too-weak-too-slow-the-uk-governments-dithering-response-to-the-wuhan-coronavirus-increases-the-risk-of-major-loss-of-life/|archive-date=22 February 2020|publisher=Technical Politics}}</ref> Some British nationals in Wuhan had been informed that they could be evacuated but any spouses or children with mainland Chinese passports could not.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-51302350|title=British mum told to leave son behind in Wuhan|date=30 January 2020|publisher=BBC News|access-date=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219182030/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-51302350|archive-date=19 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This was later overturned, but the delay meant that some people missed the flight.<ref name=\"BBC-51318691\" />\n\n=== February 2020 ===\nOn 6 February, a third confirmed case, a man who had recently travelled to Singapore prior to visiting a ski resort in the [[Haute-Savoie]], France, was reported in [[Brighton]]. He had been the source of infection to six of his relatives during a stay in France, before returning to the UK on 28 January.<ref name=\"Bosley26Feb2020\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/06/third-person-in-uk-confirmed-as-having-coronavirus|title=First British national to contract coronavirus had been in Singapore|first1=Sarah|last1=Boseley|first2=Denis|last2=Campbell|first3=Simon|last3=Murphy|date=6 February 2020|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207020202/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/06/third-person-in-uk-confirmed-as-having-coronavirus|archive-date=7 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Mohdin>{{Cite news|last=Mohdin|first=Kim Willsher Aamna|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/08/coronavirus-five-new-cases-in-france-are-british-nationals|title=Coronavirus: British nine-year-old in hospital in France|date=8 February 2020|work=The Observer|access-date=27 February 2020|url-status=live|last2=Madrid|first2=and Sam Jones in|issn=0029-7712|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226161959/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/08/coronavirus-five-new-cases-in-france-are-british-nationals|archive-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> Following confirmation of his result, the UK's CMOs expanded the number of countries where a history of previous travel associated with flu-like symptoms \u2013 such as fever, cough and difficulty breathing \u2013 in the previous 14 days would require self-isolation and calling [[NHS 111]]. These countries included China, Hong Kong, Japan, Macau, Malaysia, Republic of Korea, Singapore, Taiwan and Thailand.<ref name=\"gov.uk15Feb2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector|title=COVID-19: guidance for staff in the transport sector|publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=15 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220133756/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector|archive-date=20 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 February, the total number of cases in the UK reached eight as four further cases were confirmed in people linked to the affected man from Brighton.<ref name=BBCNews11Feb2020>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51447761|title=Coronavirus closes Brighton GP practice|date=11 February 2020|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=11 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210204845/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51447761|archive-date=10 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=PHE10Feb2020>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/chief-medical-officer-for-england-announces-four-further-coronavirus-cases|title=Chief Medical Officer for England announces four further coronavirus cases|publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=11 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210223522/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/chief-medical-officer-for-england-announces-four-further-coronavirus-cases|archive-date=10 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Globally, the virus had spread to 28 countries.<ref name=Mahase10Feb2020>{{Cite journal|last=Mahase|first=Elisabeth|date=10 February 2020|title=Coronavirus: NHS staff get power to keep patients in isolation as UK declares \"serious threat\"|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m550|journal=[[British Medical Journal]]|volume=368|pages=m550|doi=10.1136/bmj.m550|issn=1756-1833|pmid=32041792|url-access=subscription|access-date=2 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302191051/https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m550|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On the morning of 10 February, the [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]], [[Matt Hancock]], announced the [[Health Protection (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020]], to give public health professionals \"strengthened powers\" to keep affected people and those believed to be a possible risk of having the virus, in isolation.<ref name=Mahase10Feb2020/> That day, the [[Arrowe Park Hospital]], Merseyside, and the Kents Hill Park hotel and conference centre, [[Milton Keynes]] became designated isolation units.<ref name=gov.uk2Update>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-the-public|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19): latest information and advice|last=|first=|date=|website=GOV.UK|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308004037/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-the-public|archive-date=8 March 2020|access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Mahase10Feb2020/> The following day, two of the eight confirmed cases in the UK were reported by BBC News to be [[general practitioners]].<ref name=BBCNews11Feb2020/> A ninth case was confirmed in London on 11 February.<ref name=BBC12Feb2020>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51481469|title=Ninth coronavirus case found in UK|date=12 February 2020|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=12 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212193433/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51481469|archive-date=12 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== March 2020 ===\nOn 1 March, a further cases were reported in [[Greater Manchester]] of which some are believed to be contacts of the case in Surrey who had no history of travel abroad.<ref name=\"ITV1Mar2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-01/twelve-more-people-test-positive-for-coronavirus-bringing-uk-covid-19-total-to-35/|title=Twelve more people test positive for coronavirus bringing UK Covid-19 total to 35|last=|first=|date=1 March 2020|website=ITV News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301144252/https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-01/twelve-more-people-test-positive-for-coronavirus-bringing-uk-covid-19-total-to-35/|archive-date=1 March 2020|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BBCNews1March2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51697991.html|title=Coronavirus: Twelve more cases confirmed in England|last=|first=|date=1 March 2020|website=bbc.co.uk/news|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301160446/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51697991.html|archive-date=1 March 2020|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March, four further people in England tested positive. All four had recently travelled from Italy; they are from Hertfordshire, Devon and Kent.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> The total number of UK cases was reported as having reached 40, though this was revised to 39 after additional testing.<ref name=BBCNews2March2020>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51708550|title=Coronavirus could spread 'significantly' \u2013 PM|date=2 March 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=2 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302150239/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51708550|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The following day, when the total number of confirmed cases in the UK stood at 51, the UK Government unveiled their ''Coronavirus Action Plan'', which outlines what the UK has done already and what it plans to do next.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/>\n\nOn 17 March, [[NHS England]] announced that all non-urgent operations in England would be postponed from 15 April to free up 30,000 beds.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51933410 |title=Coronavirus: All non-urgent operations in England postponed |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317152225/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51933410 |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also on 17 March, [[Chancellor of the Exchequer|Chancellor]] [[Rishi Sunak]] announced that \u00a3330bn would be made available in loan guarantees for businesses affected by the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/mar/17/boris-johnson-coronavirus-press-conference-rishi-sunak-cabinet-as-rishi-sunak-set-to-announcing-coronavirus-financial-rescue-package-politics-live?page=with:block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b#block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b |title=Sunak says he will make \u00a3330bn available in lending to keep firms in business |work=The Guardian |publisher=The Guardian |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 27 March, England is the worst affected country in the United Kingdom with 12,288 confirmed infections and at least 689 deaths.<ref name=\"theg_Coro\"/>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\nBy 1 April the number of cases had increased to over 24,600 with at least 2,100 deaths.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|England]]\n[[Category:2020 in England]]\n[[Category:Health in England]]\n", "name_user": "Sharper", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:MOS: